Fig. 3
A showed the absorbance spectra of CQD, MgCQD and ZnCQD, which demonstrated an excitation wavelength at 313 nm, 320 nm, and 316 nm, respectively. From Fig. 3B, it was also observed that the emission peak wavelength was found to be at 425 nm for native CQD, whereas, for MgCQD and ZnCQD, it was observed to be 412 nm and 390 nm, respectively (Table 1
). Hence a larger stokes shift was observed for native CQD and a relatively much smaller stokes shift was observed for Zn doped CQD. The reason was due to the introduction of new electronic states in the presence of doping material. However, the maximum fluorescence emission intensity occurred when excited at nearby wavelengths, which was observed to be 330 nm (Fig. S2A) and 320 nm (Fig. S2B), respectively, for MgCQD and ZnCQD. We further investigated the direct bandgap of the material in the presence of doping material using the Tauc plot (Fig. S3). It was found that native CQD possesses the largest band gap among all, with a band gap of approximately 3.12 eV (Fig. S3A), whereas, ZnCQD exhibited the lowest bandgap, approximately 2.71 eV (Fig. S3C) and MgCQD showed a bandgap of 2.93 eV (Fig. S3B). The reason for the change of the bandgap in the presence of doping material was due to the introduction of new conduction band energy levels and intermediate energy levels. Also, the QY of the prepared samples was observed to be increased from 8.15 % (CQD) to 9.23 % (MgCQD) and 10.34 % (ZnCQD) after doping (Table S2).

Hence, there was evidence of static quenching or complex creation for MgCQD. Further, the fluorescence lifetime study was also performed to confirm the dynamic quenching (Fig. 12
                        ). It was observed for MgCQD, in the presence of Hg2+, the T2 lifetime of the whole lifetime spectra (Fig. 12A) increased to 7.05 ns from 6.25 ns (Table S12), which demonstrated the interaction between the excited electrons in MgCQD with newly available electronic levels in the presence of Hg2+ 
                        [96]. Also, for ZnCQD (Fig. 12B), the T2 lifetime drastically changed to 7.80 ns from 2.55 ns in the presence of Hg2+ (Table S12). Hence, from both the FTIR and fluorescence lifetime spectra, it was confirmed that the fluorescence quenching of both the MgCQD and ZnCQD in the presence of Hg2+ was primarily dynamic in nature.
